        "You can describe “Ain’t No Mountain High Enough” as a spiral staircase: every time the title line returns, you’re higher in the same circular space — more instruments, more choir, more echo.",
        "You can describe “Boléro” as a single straight corridor whose walls keep getting taller and more decorated, but you never change direction."
      ]
    },
    "description": "Architectural analogy helps you see sections as rooms, transitions as stairs or hallways, and builds as adding floors or opening new wings.",
    "examples_for_description": [
      "Diana Ross’s version of “Ain’t No Mountain High Enough” feels like you move from private prayer room (spoken intro) into a sanctuary filled with a whole congregation (full choir ending).",
