        "“Tom’s Diner” maps narrative calm to musical flatness: there’s no chorus lift, so the whole story feels like one long thought in the narrator’s head.",
        "“A Country Boy Can Survive” maps the moral — ‘a country boy can survive’ — to the most stable musical phrases, making the refrain feel like the spine of the story."
      ]
    },
    "description": "Narrative–music mapping lets you track where the plot turns, where the emotion spikes, and how the arrangement underlines each change.",
    "examples_for_description": [
      "Suzanne Vega deliberately avoids a chorus or big harmonic lift so the story feels like pure observation instead of drama.",
      "Hank Jr. uses the same tough groove under all verses so it feels like the narrator’s code never bends, even when the story turns tragic."
    ],
    "if_you_wanna_use_it": "Write down your key story beats, then decide what the music does at each one: stay flat, rise, darken, thin out, or explode.",
    "examples_for_if_you_wanna_use_it": [
      "Keep music steady during observational verses like “Tom’s Diner,” then only introduce a change (harmony or rhythm) when the narrator’s perception shifts.",
