    "name": "Mimesis",
    "translation": {
      "Mimesis": "imitating something from real life inside the music itself",
      "examples_for_Mimesis": [
        "In Metallica’s “One,” the rapid-fire muted picking in the bridge imitates the sound and psychological rhythm of gunfire — not metaphorically, but sonically. It’s musical imitation of real violence.",
        "In Vivaldi’s “The Four Seasons – Spring,” the violins imitate birds by using fast repeated high notes that mimic chirping."
      ],
      "combined": "using musical sounds to imitate real-world actions, machines, voices, or environments",
      "examples_for_combined": [
        "Metallica’s machine-gun bridge is mimesis at full intensity: the guitars don’t ‘represent’ war — they behave like it. That technique is one of the reasons this whole game exists.",
        "In Richard Strauss’ “Also sprach Zarathustra,” the huge rising brass chords imitate sunrise — a light swelling over the horizon."
      ]
    },
    "description": "Mimesis is when music borrows the shape, rhythm, or texture of something real — copying its movement or behavior so the listener feels they’re hearing the thing itself.",
    "examples_for_description": [
      "“One” uses picking speed and attack control to imitate automatic weapon rhythm, turning technique into storytelling.",
      "Vivaldi imitates birds, storms, and icy winds with instrumental gestures that behave like those natural sounds."
    ],
    "if_you_wanna_use_it": "Pick a real-world sound or action. Break down what makes it feel like itself — rhythm, pressure, speed, shape — and then turn those traits into instrumental patterns.",
    "examples_for_if_you_wanna_use_it": [
      "If you want machine-fire intensity, design picking patterns like the bridge of “One”: tight palms, high BPM, pulse-groupings that mimic bursts.",
      "If you want nature-mimesis, imitate the shape of the thing — long swells for wind, short flutters for birds."
    ],
    "tech_note": {
      "main": "Mimesis maps non-musical behaviors onto musical parameters (rhythm, timbre, envelope, articulation) to imitate real phenomena.",
      "common_phrasings": [
        "imitation",
        "sonic mimicry"
      ]
    }
